Problem: Three unit circles are drawn so they are mutually tangent, as shown below.  A blue circle that is externally tangent to all three unit circles is drawn.  Finally, three red circles are drawn, so that each red circle is externally tangent to two unit circles and externally tangent to the blue circle.  Then the radius of each red circle can be expressed in the form
\[\frac{a - b \sqrt{c}}{d},\]where $a,$ $b,$ $c,$ and $d$ are positive integers, when simplified.  Find $a + b + c + d$.

[asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F, O;
real s = 2/sqrt(3) - 1, r = (9 - 4*sqrt(3))/33;

A = 2/sqrt(3)*dir(150);
B = 2/sqrt(3)*dir(30);
C = 2/sqrt(3)*dir(270);
O = (0,0);
D = (r + s)*dir(330);
E = (r + s)*dir(210);
F = (r + s)*dir(90);

filldraw(Circle(O,s),blue);
filldraw(Circle(D,r),red);
filldraw(Circle(E,r),red);
filldraw(Circle(F,r),red);
draw(Circle(A,1));
draw(Circle(B,1));
draw(Circle(C,1));
[/asy]
Answer:

Let each of the three red circles have radius $r.$ Connect the centers of each pair of adjacent red circles. Then we obtain an equilateral triangle with side length $2r,$ as shown in the diagram below:

[asy]
unitsize(3 cm);

pair A, B, C, P, Q, R;

A = (1,0);
B = rotate(60)*(1,0);
C = rotate(120)*(1,0);
P = incenter(A,B,C);
Q = rotate(60)*incenter(A,B,C);
R = rotate(120)*incenter(A,B,C);

draw(circle(origin,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(P--origin);
draw(Q--origin);
draw(R--origin);
draw(P--foot(P,A,B),dashed);
draw(P--foot(P,B,C),dashed);
draw(Q--foot(Q,A,B),dashed);
draw(Q--foot(Q,B,C),dashed);
draw(R--foot(R,A,B),dashed);
draw(R--foot(R,B,C),dashed);

label("$r$", midpoint(P--Q), NW);
label("$r$", midpoint(Q--R), NE);
label("$r$", midpoint(R--P), SW);

label("$1$", midpoint(A--B), SE);
label("$1$", midpoint(B--C), NE);
label("$1$", midpoint(C--A), SW);

label("$O$", origin, SW);
[/asy]

Let $O$ be the center of the blue circle, and let $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ be the centers of the unit circles. Then $AO = 1 + r,$ and $PA = 1 - r.$ By the Pythagorean theorem, we have
\[PO^2 = AO^2 - AP^2 = (1 + r)^2 - (1 - r)^2 = 4r.\]Therefore, $PO = 2\sqrt{r}.$ Drop perpendiculars from $P,Q,$ and $R$ to $AC$ and $AB,$ as shown below:

[asy]
unitsize(3 cm);

pair A, B, C, P, Q, R;

A = (1,0);
B = rotate(60)*(1,0);
C = rotate(120)*(1,0);
P = incenter(A,B,C);
Q = rotate(60)*incenter(A,B,C);
R = rotate(120)*incenter(A,B,C);

draw(circle(origin,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(P--Q--R--cycle);
draw(P--origin);
draw(Q--origin);
draw(R--origin);
draw(P--foot(P,A,B),dashed);
draw(P--foot(P,B,C),dashed);
draw(Q--foot(Q,A,B),dashed);
draw(Q--foot(Q,B,C),dashed);
draw(R--foot(R,A,B),dashed);
draw(R--foot(R,B,C),dashed);
draw(rightanglemark(P,foot(P,A,B),B,2));
draw(rightanglemark(Q,foot(Q,A,B),B,2));
draw(rightanglemark(R,foot(R,A,B),A,2));

label("$r$", midpoint(P--Q), NW);
label("$r$", midpoint(Q--R), NE);
label("$r$", midpoint(R--P), SW);

label("$1$", midpoint(A--B), SE);
label("$1$", midpoint(B--C), NE);
label("$1$", midpoint(C--A), SW);

label("$O$", origin, SW);

label("$D$", foot(P,A,B), S);
label("$E$", foot(Q,A,B), S);
label("$F$", foot(R,A,B), N);
label("$X$", midpoint(P--Q), NE);
label("$Y$", midpoint(Q--R), N);
label("$Z$", midpoint(R--P), W);
label("$H$", foot(P,origin,Q), NW);
[/asy]

From similar triangles, we have
\[\frac{PX}{AC} = \frac{r}{1},\]so $PX = r\sqrt{3}/2.$ Therefore, $HX = PO - PX = 2\sqrt{r} - r\sqrt{3}/2.$ By the Pythagorean theorem on right triangle $PHX,$ we have
\[PH^2 = PX^2 + HX^2 = \frac{3}{4}r^2 + 4r - 3\sqrt{3} r^{3/2} + r.\]Setting this equal to $r^2$ and simplifying, we get
\[r^2 - 4r + 3\sqrt{3} r^{3/2} - \frac{3}{4}r^2 - r = 0,\]which factors as
\[\frac{(3\sqrt{3} - 7)r^{3/2}}{4} + \frac{3}{4}r - 4 = 0.\]Applying the cubic formula to solve for $r^{3/2}$ and then simplifying, we get
\[r = \frac{7 - 3\sqrt{6}}{9}.\]Therefore, $a + b + c + d = 7 + 3 + 6 + 9 = \boxed{025}.$

